r.edu/pta/phan/phan-12057/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-12057/canvas/1/97bf3ad5-cc20-4af6-8940-94c6cb2bbfcd","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T15:36:52.538Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>The black shoe polish stain embodies Alma’s strike against the Princess and what she represents in Reynolds’s life. She poisoned him, and in doing so, she led to this mark on a product of his craft. The black stain on the white dress—a striking contrast—similarly symbolizes the darkness in Reynolds and Alma’s relationship.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-12057/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:892.9118136439267,424.99168053244586,460.83194675540767,270.74875207986696"}}}]}]}]}